<br>
I have long considered my pet to be my and only my responsibility, and typically dont bother asking to the tank to try to make reasonable efforts to keep the water pet positioned behind the mob, and will typically maneuver the pet into position myself once the tank is engaged then return to my position.  If the placement of the mob changes and the pet is no longer on the back then I simply let it continue without re-positioning the pet.  I make every effort to /pet back off when the mob enrages so as to not lose the pet, and have never lost a pet to enrage except in those cases when I am in the middle of a cast and cant interrupt to issue the back off order due to an extreme circumstance.<br>
<br>
Only once has a non-guilded tank mentioned that he will try to keep the mob positioned properly after he realized that the pet has rogue backstab capabilities.  I think it is, or should be, fairly obvious to tanks that the pet is a rogue pet when they see the mage maneuvering the pet at the beginning of each fight.  Maybe many tanks are unaware of the 50+ water pet's backstab capabilities?  Maybe I should mention it when a new tank joins the group?<br>
<br>
Furthermore, I find that the pet pathing issue in dungeons is such that keeping the pet on the back of the mob is more difficult than the effort is worth.  The vast majority of my pre-PoP hunting has been done in indoor zones and thus typically use the air pet.  However, I am have access only to the Tier 1 PoP zones and find that PoD and PoN offer ample room for the positioning of mobs and PoI is the one zone that I see the pathing issue to be a problem.<br>
<br>
Again, thank you for the informative post and I hope to gain confidence in requesting and expecting the tank to be more observant of mob positioning in the future.<br>
<br>
